                    <FlowDocument>
                        <Paragraph   Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionTitle}">
                            3.1.1 Practical Approach to the Basics of Teaching Vocabulary
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            Teaching vocabulary (lexis) is essential in the classroom. When you teach English, it is common for students to come to class with new words, expressions or phrases that they have seen in manuals, at the office, in an email, heard on the radio or on TV. The more vocabulary that our students know, the easier it will be for them to be able to communicate.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>TEACHING TIP:</Bold> Students need to know at least 4000 words by the time they reach a high-intermediate level.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            When teaching new vocabulary it is essential that you present the vocabulary within a context, rather than asking students to remember random lists of words. Teach vocabulary based on categories (e.g. - clothing items, parts of the body, fruit, vegetables, etc…), and remember that students need to be able to remember whole expressions or phrases rather than just isolated words.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            One common mistake teachers make is that they tend to present too many words in one lesson and expect students to go home and memories them. We should present no more than about 10 NEW words per session as is difficult to retain any more. Memorizing endless lists of vocabulary out of context is not a communicative activity, and should therefore be avoided.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            Getting students to read texts or listen to recordings in class gives them new language input, and enables students to see exactly how these words are used in specific contexts.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            Then, give your students a reason to use this new vocabulary immediately. Design speaking or writing tasks that require the use of the new words
                        </Paragraph>
                    </FlowDocument>
                </RichTextBox>


                <RichTextBox x:Name="mod3part1sect2" Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionText}">
