                    <FlowDocument>
                        <Paragraph  Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionTitle}">
                            3.1.2 The Scope of Vocabulary Teaching Stages and Methods
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            We can usefully think of teaching vocabulary in different stages:
                        </Paragraph>
                        <List>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>Presenting new vocabulary for the first time - helping students to understand the new word</Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>Checking that students have understood the meaning of the new words</Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>Techniques for helping students expand their vocabulary</Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>Getting students to use the new words in a communicative context</Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>Periodically reviewing/revising vocabulary - helping students to remember new vocabulary</Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                        </List>
                        <Paragraph>
                            The following are some practical ideas on how to teach vocabulary:
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Elicitation</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Ask students about a particular word before you show/explain the meaning. By eliciting the meaning, we can have a student-centred classroom and the focus will be on the student and not the teacher. Students may or may not know the meaning, but if one student knows the meaning, he or she can then present it to the class.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Mind Map</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            One way of eliciting words is by putting a key word in a circle then getting students to brainstorm related words.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Flash Cards/Visual Aids</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            The use of visual aids is one of the best ways to teach a word. Showing a picture of a "football" is much easier to get the meaning across than trying to explain it. 80 per cent of our students are visual learners, so use as many visual aids as possible.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            A teacher should have their own flash cards. They can be purchased from a book store, but they can also be made from magazines, newspapers, manuals, old textbooks, etc.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Miming</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            We can mime the meaning of words to our students to give a visual cue. It is much easier to mime the verb "swim" than to try to explain the meaning in words. It would take a long time for you to explain and the class would become very teacher-centered. Miming comes from Total Physical Response (TPR) methodology, and is ideal in particular when working with young learners.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Word Definition/Translation</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Sometimes it is easier and quicker to just give students the meaning of the word, rather than eliciting or acting it out. If you know how to say it in your students' language, do so. Many words in English have different meanings and uses depending on the context. Present one or two meanings at a time rather than multiple meanings as this may confuse students.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Matching a Word with its Definition</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            If you have a number of words you are presenting for the first time, you could mix up the definitions for them. Students may already know some of them or be able to guess, and through a process of elimination, be able to work out the definitions of the others. This is made easier if they have already seen the words in a context, for example in a text or a listening.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Fill in the blank/gap</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            A very simple activity that checks vocabulary attainment by filling in missing information. We can provide our students an incomplete sentence such as:
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            Ex.: "Do you wear it on your head?" (No) "Do you wear it on your foot?" (Yes).
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Word Roots and Affixes</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            We can use the root of the word to show the meaning; when students understand/know the root, they can guess the meaning of unknown words. For example, "Bio" is a word root meaning "life"; students may be able to guess that "biology" means "the study of life". Another example is "Geo" meaning "earth" – words that begin with geo – eg, "geology" or "geometry". This technique helps students learn those words quickly.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Word Circles</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Students are given a word and they have to think of words that go with it. For example 'book' could be bookworm, book club, book case etc. These are called compound nouns or collocations.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Language Comparison</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Some of the Latin or Germanic languages have many of the same roots as English. It can be useful, if you are able to, to point out these similarities. For example, in Spanish, almost without exception, words ending in –cion or –sion have the same meaning as English words ending in -tion or –sion.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Roleplay</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Put your students in small groups. Give each group 5 of the new words learnt that day. Together they need to design a roleplay where all of the words are used in a reasonable context.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Discussions</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Create a set of discussion questions which promote the use of the new vocabulary. Put students in small groups to discuss the questions.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Ordering/Pyramid Activities</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            For some categories of words, it may be possible to ask students to list in order which are the most important for them or their favorite items. Eg, domestic electrical appliances. They would then repeat the exercise with a partner and have to reach an agreement on the order of items. The pair would then join with another pair and repeat the exercise. This is known as a Pyramid Activity.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Desert Island</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Similar to the ordering activity, but ss would be asked to decide as a group on 5 items that they would consider essential on a desert island.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Writing</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Generally, writing activities can be used to reinforce whatever students have learned in class that day. If it is vocabulary, they could be asked to write a short story incorporating the new vocab, write down the dialogue created by the roleplay, etc.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Pictionary</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Put your students into teams. You then give them a word that they have to draw on the board. The other team members have to guess what the word is.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Back to the board/Hot Seat</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            An old favorite which is always popular. One member of the team sits with their back to the board; the teacher then writes a word on the board. The other members have to explain the word without saying what it is.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>A – Z</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Students have to think of a word starting with each letter of the alphabet starting with 'A'. It can be used in categories such as words relating to clothes.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Hangman</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Great for reviewing vocabulary. Students guess the letters that go into a word while the teacher draws one part of the hangman for everyone they get wrong.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Charades</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Not only to use at Christmas! Students have to say whether it is a book, film or song and how many syllables, then act it out and the others have to guess what it is.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Provide an example</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Ask students for a sample sentence using the word, but make sure that it is in their own context.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Identifying the word</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            Very common with young learners; you can present your students with two words and the student needs to identify the one you mentioned or they heard.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            <Bold>Concept Check Questions</Bold>
                            <LineBreak/>
                            If you ask a student "do you understand?" They will probably say "yes" even if they don´t. A way of avoiding this is to use Concept Check Questions. Concept Check Questions are generally yes/no questions, to ensure that students have understood. For example, if you want to check they understand the word 'shoe' you could ask:
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            Ex.: "Do you wear it on your head?" (No) "Do you wear it on your foot?" (Yes).
                        </Paragraph>
                    </FlowDocument>
                </RichTextBox>

                <RichTextBox x:Name="mod3part1sect3" Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionText}">
