                    </RichTextBox.Effect>

                    <FlowDocument>
                        <Paragraph  Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionTitle}">
                            3.1.3 Using Dictionaries
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            The greatest single resource that students have at their disposal, whether it is in book form, electronic, online, or on CD, is a dictionary. However, these are sometimes neglected despite their wealth of information and part of teaching our students to be autonomous is to ensure that they know how (and when) to use dictionaries.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            Reference dictionaries are the most widely used. In these one can look up a word to see what it means, how it is used, and the way it is spelt and pronounced.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            Production dictionaries, on the other hand, are designed for students to use the other way around, starting with a meaning they wish to express and looking for the word that expresses it. For example, if the student wishes to express the idea of someone secretly listening to someone else while standing near him, perhaps on the other side of a door, a native speaker would immediately choose the word "eavesdrop" to describe the situation. The foreign student might find this in a bilingual dictionary, but would have more trouble with a reference dictionary since, not knowing the word in the first place, he or she would not be able to look it up. In a production dictionary, students look for a general word that they already know which is similar. In the case of "eavesdrop", for example, that word might be "listen". The student opens the production dictionary, finds the entry, and by going down the column, they come across the word which they can see, through its definitions and the examples given.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            Many teachers are frustrated by student's overuse of dictionaries, especially electronic dictionaries. Students tend to want to check the meanings of words at every stage of the lesson, therefore not giving their full attention when the teacher or other students are in the middle of saying something.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            We need to make it clear when dictionary use is appropriate and acceptable, and when it is not. They need to know that if they use their dictionaries when they should be listening, they are losing the benefit of hearing natural spoken English; and if they are reading they need to understand how important it is to read for gist (understanding) before they reach for their dictionaries to check for the meaning of words they are unfamiliar with.
                        </Paragraph>
                        <Paragraph>
                            We should, however, remain sympathetic to the student's desire to understand every word. One way to do this is to bargain with the students when they can and can't use dictionaries. This, together with our use of dictionary activities, can ensure successful and appropriate dictionary use in our lessons.
                        </Paragraph>
                    </FlowDocument>
                </RichTextBox>



                <RichTextBox x:Name="mod3part1sect4" Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionText}">
                    <RichTextBox.Effect>
                        <DropShadowEffect BlurRadius="20"  Color="Gray" Direction="315"/>
                    </RichTextBox.Effect>

                    <FlowDocument>
                        <Paragraph  Style="{StaticResource TEFLChapterSectionTitle}">
                            3.1.3a Teaching Dictionary Skills
                        </Paragraph>
                        <List>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>
                                    For low level students, you could give them some words written on cards. They then have to focus on the words at the top of the pages of the dictionaries and put the cards in the correct page of the dictionaries.
                                </Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>
                                    An interesting activity to get the 'feel' of the relative numbers of words each section of a dictionary has is to shout out a letter. Students then have to just hold those pages from the dictionary with words for that letter. It is interesting to see that 'Q', for example, has a lot less words than 'S'.
                                </Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>
                                    A popular classroom activity is Call My Bluff. The class is divided into teams. One team chooses the most difficult word they can find in the dictionary and writes the definition on a piece of paper. The other teams write what they think will be the definition on their pieces of paper. Each team has to decide which definition is correct. Of course, the only team that knows the real answer is the one with the dictionary.
                                </Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>
                                    When working on phrasal verbs, students can be asked to find all the phrasal verbs that go with, for example, come. You will be surprised how many there are.
                                </Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                            <ListItem Style="{StaticResource SpacedListItem}">
                                <Paragraph>
                                    Any good dictionary will have phonemic symbols next to the words. Students can be asked to write the phonemic spelling of the word on a piece of paper; it is then passed to the next pair who then has to try to work out what the real word is.
                                </Paragraph>
                            </ListItem>
                        </List>
                    </FlowDocument>
                </RichTextBox>

